T1  - Is the Fisher effect for real?: A reexamination of the relationship between inflation and interest rates
AU  - Mishkin, Frederic S.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 30
IS  - 2
SP  - 195
EP  - 215
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/11/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(92)90060-F
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329290060F
AB  - This paper resolves the puzzle of why a strong Fisher effect (a high correlation between the level of interest rates and inflation) occurs only during certain periods but not for others. Empirical evidence finds no support for a short-run Fisher effect in which a change in expected inflation is associated with a change in interest rates, but supports the existence of a long-run Fisher effect in which inflation and interest rates have a common stochastic trend when they exhibit trends. These results indicate that a strong Fisher effect will only appear in samples where inflation and interest rates have trends.
